[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 9.4: Python Implementation Example
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Heads up:** This is a deliberately simplified, illustrative implementation of the pseudocode walkthrough from Recipe 9.4. It shows one way you could wire up the dermatology lesion triage pipeline using boto3 and basic image processing. It is not production-ready. There's no real trained model here (we simulate inference for demonstration), no FDA-compliant validation suite, and no clinical workflow integration. Think of it as the wiring diagram: useful for understanding how the pieces connect, not something you'd point at real patient photos on Monday morning. Consider it a starting point, not a destination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Setup
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You'll need the AWS SDK for Python and a few image processing libraries:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```bash
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m pip install boto3 pillow numpy
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Your environment needs credentials configured (via environment variables, an instance profile, or `~/.aws/credentials`). The IAM role or user needs:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint` (for the classification model)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `s3:PutObject`, `s3:GetObject` (for image storage)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:GetItem` (for case tracking)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `sns:Publish` (for urgent case notifications)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Config and Constants
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Before we get to the pipeline steps, here's the configuration that drives triage decisions. These thresholds are clinical decisions made in collaboration with dermatology leadership, not engineering choices. They determine the sensitivity/specificity tradeoff and will need adjustment as you gather real-world outcome data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # TRIAGE_THRESHOLDS: Clinical decision thresholds for routing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # These numbers determine how aggressively the system escalates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Lower URGENT_THRESHOLD = more cases flagged urgent = higher sensitivity but more false alarms.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Higher URGENT_THRESHOLD = fewer urgent flags = fewer false alarms but risk of missed melanomas.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Set these with your dermatology department. Review quarterly against outcome data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # The values below are illustrative starting points, not validated clinical thresholds.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m TRIAGE_THRESHOLDS = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "urgent": 0.70,       # Above this: immediate dermatology review
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "suspicious": 0.40,   # Above this: expedited scheduling (within 2 weeks)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Below suspicious: standard follow-up recommendation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # IMAGE_QUALITY_THRESHOLDS: Minimum quality requirements before running inference.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Rejecting bad images early saves compute cost and prevents garbage predictions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # from eroding clinician trust in the system.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m IMAGE_QUALITY_THRESHOLDS = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "min_dimension": 224,       # Pixels. Model input size; below this there's not enough detail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "blur_threshold": 100.0,    # Laplacian variance. Below this = too blurry to trust.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "min_brightness": 40,       # Mean pixel value. Below this = too dark.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "max_brightness": 220,      # Mean pixel value. Above this = overexposed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # MODEL_CONFIG: SageMaker endpoint configuration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Replace these with your actual endpoint name and input specifications.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m MODEL_CONFIG = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "endpoint_name": "lesion-classifier-v2",    # Your SageMaker endpoint
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "input_size": 224,                          # Model expects 224x224 input
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "content_type": "application/x-npy",        # NumPy array format for this example
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # ImageNet normalization parameters (standard for models pre-trained on ImageNet)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "normalize_mean": [0.485, 0.456, 0.406],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "normalize_std": [0.229, 0.224, 0.225],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # TRIAGE_CATEGORIES: Maps model output indices to human-readable category names.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # The model outputs a probability for each class in this order.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m TRIAGE_CATEGORIES = ["benign", "suspicious", "urgent"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # AWS resource names. Replace with your actual resource names.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m S3_BUCKET = "lesion-images-phi"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m DYNAMODB_TABLE = "triage-cases"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SNS_TOPIC_ARN = "arn:aws:sns:us-east-1:123456789012:urgent-derm-triage"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Step 1: Image Quality Validation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *The pseudocode calls this `validate_image_quality(image_bytes)`. Before spending compute on inference, verify the submitted image is actually usable. A blurry bathroom selfie with bad lighting will produce meaningless predictions.*
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import io
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import logging
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import numpy as np
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from PIL import Image
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m logger.setLevel(logging.INFO)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def validate_image_quality(image_bytes: bytes) -> dict:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Check whether a lesion photo meets minimum quality requirements.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     This is a fast, cheap gate that runs before the expensive ML inference step.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     It catches the most common failure modes: blurry photos, too dark, too bright,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     or too low resolution to be useful.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         image_bytes: Raw bytes of the uploaded image (JPEG or PNG).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         A dict with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         - "valid": bool indicating whether the image passes all checks
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         - "reason": human-readable explanation if invalid (for user feedback)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         - "metrics": the computed quality metrics (for logging/debugging)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Decode the image bytes into a PIL Image object.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     image = Image.open(io.BytesIO(image_bytes)).convert("RGB")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     width, height = image.size
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Convert to numpy array for numerical analysis.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     pixels = np.array(image, dtype=np.float32)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Check 1: Resolution.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # The classification model expects 224x224 input. If the source image is
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # smaller than that, we'd be upscaling (inventing pixels), which degrades
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # accuracy. Require at least the model's input size.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     if width < IMAGE_QUALITY_THRESHOLDS["min_dimension"] or height < IMAGE_QUALITY_THRESHOLDS["min_dimension"]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         return {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "valid": False,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "reason": "Image resolution too low. Please move closer to the lesion.",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "metrics": {"width": width, "height": height},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Check 2: Blur detection using Laplacian variance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # The Laplacian operator highlights edges. A sharp image has lots of strong
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # edges (high variance). A blurry image has weak, smeared edges (low variance).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # We compute this on the grayscale version of the image.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     gray = np.mean(pixels, axis=2)  # Simple grayscale conversion
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Laplacian kernel (approximation): highlights second-order intensity changes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # scipy would be cleaner here, but we keep dependencies minimal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     laplacian = (
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         gray[:-2, 1:-1] + gray[2:, 1:-1] + gray[1:-1, :-2] + gray[1:-1, 2:]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         - 4 * gray[1:-1, 1:-1]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     blur_score = float(np.var(laplacian))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     if blur_score < IMAGE_QUALITY_THRESHOLDS["blur_threshold"]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         return {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "valid": False,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "reason": "Image appears blurry. Please hold steady and ensure the camera is focused.",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "metrics": {"blur_score": blur_score},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Check 3: Brightness.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Too dark = lost detail in shadows. Too bright = washed out, lost color info.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     mean_brightness = float(np.mean(pixels))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     if mean_brightness < IMAGE_QUALITY_THRESHOLDS["min_brightness"]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         return {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "valid": False,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "reason": "Image too dark. Please improve lighting.",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "metrics": {"mean_brightness": mean_brightness},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     if mean_brightness > IMAGE_QUALITY_THRESHOLDS["max_brightness"]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         return {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "valid": False,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "reason": "Image too bright or overexposed. Reduce direct light on the lesion.",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "metrics": {"mean_brightness": mean_brightness},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "valid": True,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "reason": None,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "metrics": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "width": width,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "height": height,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "blur_score": blur_score,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "mean_brightness": mean_brightness,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Step 2: Image Preprocessing
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *The pseudocode calls this `preprocess_image(image_bytes, target_size)`. The classification model expects a specific input format: fixed dimensions, normalized pixel values, channel-wise standardization matching the training pipeline. If you preprocess differently than the training data was preprocessed, accuracy degrades silently.*
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def preprocess_image(image_bytes: bytes) -> bytes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Transform a raw lesion photo into the format the classification model expects.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     This must exactly match the preprocessing used during model training.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Differences in resize interpolation, normalization range, or channel ordering
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     will silently degrade accuracy without any error message.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         image_bytes: Raw bytes of the validated image.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Serialized numpy array ready to send to the SageMaker endpoint.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     target_size = MODEL_CONFIG["input_size"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     mean = np.array(MODEL_CONFIG["normalize_mean"], dtype=np.float32)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     std = np.array(MODEL_CONFIG["normalize_std"], dtype=np.float32)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Load and resize to model input dimensions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # LANCZOS resampling preserves detail better than bilinear for downscaling.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Most training pipelines use bilinear or bicubic; match yours.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     image = Image.open(io.BytesIO(image_bytes)).convert("RGB")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     image = image.resize((target_size, target_size), Image.LANCZOS)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Convert to float32 numpy array and normalize to [0, 1].
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Raw pixel values are 0-255 integers. Neural networks expect small floats.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     pixels = np.array(image, dtype=np.float32) / 255.0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Apply ImageNet channel-wise normalization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # This centers each color channel around zero with unit variance,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # matching what the pre-trained backbone (EfficientNet, ResNet, etc.)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # was trained on. Without this, the first layers produce wrong activations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     pixels = (pixels - mean) / std
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Serialize as numpy bytes. SageMaker endpoints can accept various formats;
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # numpy is straightforward for image data. Your endpoint's input handler
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # must match this serialization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     buffer = io.BytesIO()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     np.save(buffer, pixels)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return buffer.getvalue()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Step 3: Model Inference
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *The pseudocode calls this `classify_lesion(preprocessed_payload, endpoint_name)`. Send the preprocessed image to the SageMaker endpoint and get back a probability distribution across triage categories.*
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import boto3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from botocore.config import Config
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Adaptive retry handles transient throttling from SageMaker under load.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG = Config(retries={"max_attempts": 3, "mode": "adaptive"})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m sagemaker_runtime = boto3.client("sagemaker-runtime", config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def classify_lesion(preprocessed_payload: bytes) -> dict:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Invoke the SageMaker endpoint to classify a preprocessed lesion image.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     The endpoint hosts a trained CNN (e.g., EfficientNet fine-tuned on ISIC data)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     that outputs a probability distribution across triage categories.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         preprocessed_payload: Serialized numpy array from preprocess_image().
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Dict mapping category names to probabilities.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Example: {"benign": 0.22, "suspicious": 0.68, "urgent": 0.10}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     response = sagemaker_runtime.invoke_endpoint(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         EndpointName=MODEL_CONFIG["endpoint_name"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ContentType=MODEL_CONFIG["content_type"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Body=preprocessed_payload,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Parse the model's response. The exact format depends on your model server
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # (TorchServe, TensorFlow Serving, custom inference.py, etc.).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # This assumes the endpoint returns a JSON array of probabilities
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # in the same order as TRIAGE_CATEGORIES.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     result_body = response["Body"].read().decode("utf-8")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     probabilities = json.loads(result_body)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Map the raw probability array to named categories.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     predictions = {}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     for i, category in enumerate(TRIAGE_CATEGORIES):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         predictions[category] = float(probabilities[i])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return predictions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Step 4: Triage Decision Logic
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *The pseudocode calls this `determine_triage(predictions)`. Translate raw model probabilities into an actionable triage decision. The thresholds here are clinical decisions, not engineering ones.*
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def determine_triage(predictions: dict) -> dict:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Apply clinical thresholds to model predictions and produce a triage decision.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     The logic is simple: check urgent first (highest priority), then suspicious,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     then default to routine. If both urgent and suspicious are above threshold,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     urgent wins because patient safety takes priority over queue efficiency.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         predictions: Dict of category -> probability from classify_lesion().
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Dict with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         - "category": URGENT, SUSPICIOUS, or ROUTINE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         - "action": Human-readable recommendation for the clinician
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         - "confidence": The probability score for the assigned category
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         - "all_scores": Full probability distribution (for audit trail)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     urgent_score = predictions.get("urgent", 0.0)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     suspicious_score = predictions.get("suspicious", 0.0)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     benign_score = predictions.get("benign", 0.0)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Check urgent first. A high urgent score means the model sees features
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # consistent with melanoma or other aggressive lesions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     if urgent_score >= TRIAGE_THRESHOLDS["urgent"]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         return {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "category": "URGENT",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "action": "Immediate dermatology review recommended",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "confidence": urgent_score,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "all_scores": predictions,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Check suspicious next. Features that don't scream "urgent" but warrant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # closer inspection sooner than the standard 30-90 day wait.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     if suspicious_score >= TRIAGE_THRESHOLDS["suspicious"]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         return {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "category": "SUSPICIOUS",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "action": "Expedited dermatology appointment recommended (within 2 weeks)",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "confidence": suspicious_score,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "all_scores": predictions,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Default: the model's highest confidence is in the benign category.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Standard monitoring with instructions to return if changes are observed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "category": "ROUTINE",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "action": "Standard monitoring. Follow up if changes observed.",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "confidence": benign_score,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "all_scores": predictions,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Step 5: Store Results and Notify
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *The pseudocode calls this `store_and_notify(case_id, patient_id, image_key, triage_result)`. Every triage case gets a permanent record for the dermatologist review queue, audit trail, and outcome tracking.*
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import datetime
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import uuid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from datetime import timezone
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from decimal import Decimal
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m dynamodb = boto3.resource("dynamodb")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m sns_client = boto3.client("sns", config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def store_and_notify(patient_id: str, image_key: str, triage_result: dict) -> dict:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Write the triage record to DynamoDB and send notifications for urgent cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     This record serves three purposes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     1. The dermatology review queue pulls cases by priority.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     2. The audit trail shows what the AI recommended and when.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     3. Outcome tracking (dermatologist's actual diagnosis) enables model monitoring.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_id: De-identified patient identifier.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         image_key:  S3 key of the original lesion image.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         triage_result: Output from determine_triage().
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         The complete case record that was written.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     table = dynamodb.Table(DYNAMODB_TABLE)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Generate a unique case ID. In production, you might use a more structured
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # format that encodes date and facility for easier querying.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     case_id = f"TRIAGE-{datetime.date.today().isoformat()}-{uuid.uuid4().hex[:8]}"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # DynamoDB requires Decimal for numeric values, not float.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Wrap all scores in Decimal via string conversion to avoid floating-point artifacts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     all_scores_decimal = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         k: Decimal(str(round(v, 4))) for k, v in triage_result["all_scores"].items()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     record = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "case_id": case_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "patient_id": patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "image_key": image_key,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "triage_category": triage_result["category"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "triage_action": triage_result["action"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "model_confidence": Decimal(str(round(triage_result["confidence"], 4))),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "all_scores": all_scores_decimal,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "submitted_at": datetime.datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "reviewed_by": None,            # Populated when dermatologist reviews
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "dermatologist_dx": None,       # Populated with actual diagnosis
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "status": "PENDING_REVIEW",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     table.put_item(Item=record)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Stored triage case %s with category %s", case_id, triage_result["category"])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # For urgent cases, send an immediate notification.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Don't rely on someone polling the queue for time-sensitive findings.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     if triage_result["category"] == "URGENT":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         sns_client.publish(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             TopicArn=SNS_TOPIC_ARN,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             Subject=f"URGENT Lesion Triage: {case_id}",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             Message=(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 f"Urgent lesion triage case requires immediate review.\n\n"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 f"Case ID: {case_id}\n"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 f"Patient: {patient_id}\n"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 f"Model confidence: {triage_result['confidence']:.2%}\n"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 f"Action: {triage_result['action']}\n"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             ),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         logger.info("Sent urgent notification for case %s", case_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return record
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Step 6: Upload Image to S3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *Before running the pipeline, the original image needs to land in encrypted S3 storage. This gives us a durable, auditable record of exactly what was submitted.*
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m s3_client = boto3.client("s3", config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def upload_image(image_bytes: bytes, patient_id: str, filename: str) -> str:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Store the original lesion image in S3 with server-side KMS encryption.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     The S3 key structure organizes images by date and patient for easy retrieval.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     The original image is preserved exactly as submitted (no preprocessing)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     so the dermatologist sees what the patient actually photographed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         image_bytes: Raw image bytes as submitted.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_id:  De-identified patient identifier.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         filename:    Original filename (for extension detection).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         The S3 object key where the image was stored.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     today = datetime.date.today().isoformat()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Structure: lesion-images/{date}/{patient_id}/{unique_id}.{ext}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ext = filename.rsplit(".", 1)[-1] if "." in filename else "jpg"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     unique_id = uuid.uuid4().hex[:12]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     key = f"lesion-images/{today}/{patient_id}/{unique_id}.{ext}"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     s3_client.put_object(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Bucket=S3_BUCKET,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Key=key,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Body=image_bytes,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ContentType=f"image/{ext}",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ServerSideEncryption="aws:kms",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # In production, specify your KMS key ID explicitly:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # SSEKMSKeyId="arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:123456789012:key/your-key-id"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Uploaded image to s3://%s/%s", S3_BUCKET, key)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return key
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Putting It All Together
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's the full pipeline assembled into a single function. This is what your Lambda handler or API endpoint would call.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def triage_lesion(image_bytes: bytes, patient_id: str, filename: str) -> dict:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Run the full dermatology lesion triage pipeline for one submitted image.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     This is the main entry point. In a Lambda deployment, your handler would
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     parse the API Gateway event, extract the image bytes and patient ID,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     and call this function.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         image_bytes: Raw bytes of the submitted lesion photo.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_id:  De-identified patient identifier.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         filename:    Original filename of the uploaded image.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Dict with either:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         - A triage result (case_id, category, action, confidence) on success
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         - A rejection reason if the image fails quality checks
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    489[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Step 1: Quality validation. Reject unusable images before spending
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    490[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # compute on inference. Return actionable feedback so the user can retake.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    491[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Step 1: Validating image quality")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    492[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     quality = validate_image_quality(image_bytes)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    493[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     if not quality["valid"]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    494[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         logger.info("  Image rejected: %s", quality["reason"])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    495[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         return {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    496[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "status": "REJECTED",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    497[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "reason": quality["reason"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    498[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "metrics": quality["metrics"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    499[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    500[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("  Quality OK: %s", quality["metrics"])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    501[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    502[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Step 2: Upload the original image to S3 for audit trail and dermatologist review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    503[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Step 2: Uploading image to S3")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    504[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     image_key = upload_image(image_bytes, patient_id, filename)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    505[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    506[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Step 3: Preprocess the image to match model input requirements.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    507[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Step 3: Preprocessing image for model input")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    508[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     preprocessed = preprocess_image(image_bytes)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    509[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    510[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Step 4: Run inference on the SageMaker endpoint.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    511[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Step 4: Invoking classification model")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    512[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     predictions = classify_lesion(preprocessed)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    513[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("  Predictions: %s", predictions)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    514[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    515[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Step 5: Apply clinical thresholds to determine triage category.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    516[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Step 5: Determining triage category")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    517[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     triage_result = determine_triage(predictions)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    518[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("  Triage: %s (confidence: %.2f)", triage_result["category"], triage_result["confidence"])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    519[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    520[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Step 6: Store the case record and notify if urgent.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    521[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Step 6: Storing result and sending notifications")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    522[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     record = store_and_notify(patient_id, image_key, triage_result)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    523[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    524[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Done. Case %s -> %s", record["case_id"], record["triage_category"])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    525[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    526[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "status": "TRIAGED",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    527[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "case_id": record["case_id"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    528[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "triage_category": record["triage_category"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    529[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "triage_action": record["triage_action"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    530[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "model_confidence": float(record["model_confidence"]),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    531[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "all_scores": {k: float(v) for k, v in record["all_scores"].items()},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    532[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    533[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    534[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    535[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Example usage with a local test image.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    536[0m:[38;5;10m[49m if __name__ == "__main__":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    537[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Load a test image (never use real patient photos in development).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    538[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Use synthetic or public dataset images (ISIC archive) for testing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    539[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     import sys
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    540[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    541[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     if len(sys.argv) < 2:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    542[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         print("Usage: python triage_pipeline.py <image_path> [patient_id]")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    543[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         sys.exit(1)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    544[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    545[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     image_path = sys.argv[1]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    546[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     patient_id = sys.argv[2] if len(sys.argv) > 2 else "TEST-PATIENT-001"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    547[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    548[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     with open(image_path, "rb") as f:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    549[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         image_data = f.read()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    550[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    551[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     result = triage_lesion(image_data, patient_id, image_path.split("/")[-1])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    552[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     print(json.dumps(result, indent=2, default=str))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    553[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    554[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    555[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    556[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    557[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Gap Between This and Production
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    558[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    559[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This example shows how the pieces connect. Run it against a test image with a deployed SageMaker endpoint and it will return a triage decision. But there's a meaningful distance between "works in a script" and "runs in a clinic triaging real patient photos." Here's where that gap lives:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    560[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    561[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Model training and validation.** This example assumes you have a trained model deployed to a SageMaker endpoint. Actually training that model is a significant effort: curating a balanced dataset across skin tones and lesion types, implementing proper train/validation/test splits stratified by patient (not just by image), validating performance across Fitzpatrick skin types I-VI, and documenting the model card with intended use, limitations, and performance metrics. The model training pipeline is a separate project.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    562[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    563[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Bias validation.** Before deploying to any patient population, you must measure and document model performance stratified by skin tone. If sensitivity drops below acceptable thresholds for any Fitzpatrick type, the model is not ready for that population. This isn't a nice-to-have. It's an equity requirement with real clinical consequences. Build a validation dataset that's representative of your actual patient demographics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    564[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    565[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Error handling and graceful degradation.** This code lets exceptions propagate. A production system catches specific failure modes: SageMaker endpoint throttling (retry with backoff), endpoint model errors (return "unable to triage, routing to manual review"), S3 upload failures (retry, then queue for later), DynamoDB write failures (dead-letter queue). The system should never silently lose a submission.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    566[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    567[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Input validation and security.** This code trusts its inputs. A production system validates: file size limits (reject multi-GB uploads), file type verification (check magic bytes, not just extension), image dimension bounds, and patient ID format. Malformed inputs should be rejected at the API Gateway level before reaching Lambda.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    568[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    569[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Capture UX and guidance.** The quality gate rejects bad images, but the real solution is preventing bad images in the first place. A production system includes a capture interface with: real-time focus and lighting feedback, positioning guides (distance, angle), reference markers for scale, and clear instructions. The capture UX is as important as the model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    570[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    571[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Regulatory documentation.** If this system's output influences clinical decisions (even as "triage only"), you need: a clear intended use statement, a clinical validation study, a model card documenting performance and limitations, a risk analysis (what happens when the model is wrong?), and regulatory counsel's sign-off on whether this constitutes a medical device under FDA guidance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    572[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    573[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome tracking and model monitoring.** The `dermatologist_dx` field in the case record exists for a reason. You need a process for dermatologists to record their actual diagnosis back to the triage record. Without this feedback loop, you can't measure real-world model performance, detect drift, or know if your thresholds are calibrated correctly. Build the outcome recording workflow before you deploy the model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    574[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    575[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Threshold calibration.** The thresholds in this example (0.70 for urgent, 0.40 for suspicious) are illustrative. Real thresholds must be calibrated on a held-out validation set with known outcomes, in collaboration with dermatology leadership. They represent a clinical decision about the sensitivity/specificity tradeoff, and they'll need periodic adjustment as you gather outcome data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    576[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    577[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **VPC and network isolation.** Lesion photographs are PHI. In production, Lambda and the SageMaker endpoint run inside a VPC with private subnets. VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, SageMaker Runtime, and SNS keep all traffic on the AWS backbone. No PHI traverses the public internet, even though TLS encrypts everything in transit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    578[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    579[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Encryption key management.** This example uses default SSE-KMS encryption. Production uses customer-managed KMS keys with: key rotation enabled, CloudTrail logging of every key usage, separate keys for different data classifications, and key policies that restrict access to specific IAM roles.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    580[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    581[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Logging and audit.** The `logger.info()` calls here are a starting point. Production logging uses structured JSON output (AWS Lambda Powertools is excellent for this) with consistent fields: case_id, patient_id (hashed), step name, duration, and outcome. Never log the image content, model predictions with patient identifiers, or any data that could reconstruct PHI from logs alone.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    582[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    583[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Testing.** There are no tests here. A production pipeline has: unit tests for each step with mocked AWS calls, integration tests against a real SageMaker endpoint with known test images from public datasets, performance tests measuring end-to-end latency under load, and a regression test suite that runs against every model version before deployment. Never use real patient photos in test fixtures.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    584[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    585[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    586[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    587[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *Part of the Healthcare AI/ML Cookbook. See [Recipe 9.4](chapter09.04-dermatology-lesion-triage.md) for the full architectural walkthrough, pseudocode, and honest take on where this gets hard.*
